1 BRIEF INTRODUCTION

1.1 DNA methylation

DNA methylation (DNAm) is an epigenetic mechanism that occurs by the addition of a methyl group to DNA. It can occur at different genome locations: gene bodies, promoter regions, or non-coding areas. The location of the methylation will often have an impact on gene regulation, modifying gene function and affecting gene expression. We will analyze a test data in RStudio using standard workflow pipeliens minfi and ChAMP.

DNAm basic analysis follows a standard omic data analysis approach, which consists of several steps. From pre-processing of data and filtering (quality check, filtering poor quality probes/samples, chromosome X and Y, probes over SNPs and cross-reactive probes) to normalization, cell type deconvolution analysis, singular value decomposition analysis for confounder identification, correction of technical biases (batch effects) and identification of differentially methylated CpG sites (DMCs), genes (DMGs) or regions (DMRs). Finally the genes are mapped to the pathways to see the enrichment.

1.2 DATASET

To demonstrate the various aspects of analyzing DNA methylation data, we will be using a data, publicly available PMID: 27942592 Illumina Infinium array, 450k methylation dataset GSE85566. Genome-wide methylation data was generated from freshly isolated airway epithelial cells from 74 asthmatic and 41 nonasthmatic adults.

We will import and read the raw data intensity files (IDAT) with minfi package. The dataset Raw_data have been provided to you in your Lab_assignment4 folder already, so you just need to point R towards the directory path they are saved.

  • list.files function will return the list of files in the specified directory.

In the resulting plot, the line separating ”bad” from ”good” samples represent a useful cutoff, which is not always very clear and may have to be adapted to a specific dataset.

2.5.2 DetectionP

The function detectionP calculate detection p-values. We can generate a detection p-value for every CpG in every sample, which is indicative of the quality of the signal. The method used by minfi to calculate detection p-values compares the total signal (M + U) for each probe to the background signal level, which is estimated from the negative control probes. Very small p-values are indicative of a reliable signal while large p-values, for example >0.01, generally indicate a poor quality signal.

  detP <- detectionP(rgSet)

# This will plot the control probe signals. Read more at '?controlStripPlot' 
  controlStripPlot(rgSet, controls="BISULFITE CONVERSION II")

Plotting the mean detection p-value for each sample allows us to gauge the general quality of the samples in terms of the overall signal reliability. Samples that have many failed probes will have relatively large mean detection p-values.

# examine mean detection p-values across all samples to identify any failed samples
  pal <- col1
  par(mfrow=c(1,2))
  barplot(colMeans(detP), col=col1, las=2,
           cex.names=0.8,ylab="Mean detection p-values")
  abline(h=0.01,col="red")
  legend("topleft", legend=levels(factor(targets$Sample_Group)), fill=pal,
          bg="white")
  
  barplot(colMeans(detP), col=col1, las=2,
           cex.names=0.8, ylim = c(0,0.05), ylab="Mean detection p-values")
  abline(h=0.01,col="red")
  legend("topleft", legend=levels(factor(targets$Sample_Group)), fill=pal,
          bg="white")

# remove poor quality samples

2.6 NORMALIZATION

To minimise the unwanted variation within and between samples, various data normalisations can be applied. Many different types of normalisation have been developed for methylation arrays which are available in minfi. An important question is to decide which one is best or most optimal for your particular dataset. Here is a short summary of each method:

preprocessRaw: Converts a RGChannelSet to a MethylSet by converting the Red and Green channels into a matrix of methylated signals and a matrix of unmethylated signals. No normalization is performed.

preprocessIllumina: Convert a RGChannelSet to a MethylSet by implementing the preprocessing choices as available in Genome Studio: background subtraction and control normalization. Both of them are optional and turning them off is equivalent to raw preprocessing.

preprocessSWAN: Perform Subset-quantile within array normalization SWAN, a within-array normalization correction for the technical differences between the Type I and Type II array designs.


NOTE! It is recommended in case of global biological methylation differences between your samples for example dataset with cancer and normal samples, or a dataset with different tissues/cell types, use the preprocessFunnorm Funnorm function. While incases where you do not expect global differences between your samples, for instance a blood dataset, or one-tissue dataset, use the preprocessQuantile Quantile normalization function. 
  # normalize the data; this results in a GenomicRatioSet object
    mSetSw <- preprocessSWAN(rgSet)

Density Plot after Normalization

# Visualise what the data looks like before and after normalization

#Density plot 
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

2.7 FILTERING

Poor performing probes are generally filtered out before differential methylation analysis. By removing them we perform fewer statistical tests and reduced multiple testing penalty. Following probes are filtered away:

  • Probes that have failed in one or more samples based on detection p-value.
  • Depending on the nature of your samples and your biological question you may also choose to filter out the probes from the X and Y chromosomes
  • Probes that are known to have common SNPs at the CpG site
  • Probes that are cross-reactive.
# ensure probes are in the same order in the mSetSw and detP objects
    detP <- detP[match(featureNames(mSetSw),rownames(detP)),]
  
#1 remove any probes that have failed in one or more samples; this next line
    keep <- rowSums(detP < 0.01) == ncol(mSetSw)
    table(keep)
## keep
##  FALSE   TRUE 
##   3647 481865
    # Subset the GenomicRatioSet
    mSetSwFlt.bf <- mSetSw[keep,]
    # mSetSwFlt.bf contains the probes before X and Y filtering
    dim(mSetSwFlt.bf) 
## [1] 481865    115
#2 if your data includes males and females, remove probes on the sex chromosomes
    keep <- !(featureNames(mSetSwFlt.bf) %in% ann450k$Name[ann450k$chr %in%
                                                                   c("chrX","chrY")])
    table(keep)
## keep
##  FALSE   TRUE 
##  11175 470690
    mSetSwFlt <- mSetSwFlt.bf[keep,]
    dim(mSetSwFlt)
## [1] 470690    115
#3 remove probes with SNPs at CpG site
    gset <- mapToGenome(mSetSwFlt)
    mSetSwFlt <- dropLociWithSnps(gset)
    dim(mSetSwFlt)
## [1] 454707    115
    dim(samples)
## [1] 115  12

    dim(mSetSwFlt)

2.8 BETA Values and M-values

Beta-value represents the ratio of the methylated probe intensity to the overall intensity. It is commonly used to quantify the level of methylation at a specific CpG site. Beta value range from 0 (unmethylated) to 1 (fully methylated).

  • Beta = M/(M + U + 100)
  • Mvalue = log2(M/U)
# Calculation of M values and beta values
    mVals <- getM(mSetSwFlt)
    bVals <- getBeta(mSetSwFlt)
    head(bVals[,1:5])

2.9 SINGULAR VALUE DECOMPOSITION

Singular value decomposition (SVD) analyses is performed to identify major sources of variation using the ChAMP package champ.SVD function. Analyses on the filtered and normalized beta matrix are performed.

Any confounding components that contributed to significant variation within the data set is identified using SVD. You get two plots as a result of the champ.SVD

  • Scree-plot: shows Percent variance explained by each component
  • Heatmap of SVD: shows the variables (age, sex, slide, array etc.) explaining significant variance (darker the color, more significant variance explained).
# Select PD file covariates to analyze
    samples_svd <- samples
    samples_svd [] <- lapply(samples_svd, as.character) # set all variables to character


# SVD before correction
    champ.SVD(beta=as.data.frame(bVals),pd=samples_svd,Rplot = TRUE,resultsDir = "Results/Figures/")

2.10 BATCH EFFECT CORRECTION

Based on SVD, corrections are performed for the identified components using Combat from the SVA package. This allows us to identify any technical bias in data and correct for any batch affects or confounders.

# Batch correction on beta-values
    batchname <- c("Slide", "Array")
        beta_corr <- bVals ## giving the normalized beta matrix only
        for (batchvar in batchname){
          beta_corr <- ComBat(
            dat=beta_corr,
            batch=samples[, batchvar],
            mod = NULL, ## this is where we donot give the variable of interest
          )
        }
        bVals.corrected <- beta_corr
# Batch correction on M-values
    batchname <- c("Slide", "Array")
        MVal_corr <- mVals ## giving the normalized beta matrix only
        for (batchvar in batchname){
          MVal_corr <- ComBat(
            dat=MVal_corr,
            batch=samples[, batchvar],
            mod = NULL, ## this is where we donot give the variable of interest
          )
        }
        mVals.corrected <- MVal_corr
  
# SVD after correction
    champ.SVD(beta=as.data.frame(bVals.corrected),pd=samples_svd,Rplot = TRUE,resultsDir = "Results/Figures/")

2.12 DIFFERENTIAL METHYLATION

The biological question of interest for this particular dataset is to discover differentially methylated CpGs (DMCs) between the Asthma vs Control group.

  • To do this, we will design a linear model in limma package (See manual for details). As previously seen, the sex contributed as significant source of variation and could be confounding factor in this analysis. Therefore, we will use sex as co-variate in the design matrix.

  • Using the topTable function in limma, the differentially methylated genes per comparison/contrast can be extracted.

2.12.1 Differentially methylated CpGs (DMC)

# Define the factor of interest i.e. Sample group with CFS vs non_CFS
  group <- factor(samples$Sample_Group)

# Define the confounding factor that need to be taken into account i.e sex
  sex <- factor(samples$Gender)
  smoker <- factor(samples$current_smoker)
  
# Design the matrix with group as our main variable of interest and sex as co-variate.
  design<-model.matrix(~0+group+sex+smoker,data=samples)

  colnames(design) <- c(levels(group),"sex","smoker")
  contMatrix <- makeContrasts(Asthma-Control,levels=design)

# fit the actual linear model to the data
  
# NOTE!! Here we are using beta value: bVals.corrected BUT mVals.corrected can be used.
  fit<-lmFit(bVals.corrected,design) 
  colnames(fit$coefficients)
## [1] "Asthma"  "Control" "sex"     "smoker"
  rownames(contMatrix)
## [1] "Asthma"  "Control" "sex"     "smoker"
  fit2 <- contrasts.fit(fit, contMatrix)
  fit2 <- eBayes(fit2)
  summary(decideTests(fit2))
##        Asthma - Control
## Down               8672
## NotSig           404555
## Up                15027
  # Annotate the DMCs using cleaned annotation object loaded above
  annot_combat <- annot[match(rownames(bVals.corrected),annot$CpG_ID),
                               c(1:ncol(annot))]
  # DMC full set
  DMCs<-topTable(fit2,coef = 1,number = Inf,genelist = annot_combat)
  
  # top DMCs based on FDR adj.P.Val < 0.05 cutoff and logFC > 0.1
  # You can adjust the cutoffs based on given datasets
  
  topset1<-subset(DMCs, DMCs$adj.P.Val<0.05 & abs(DMCs$logFC)>0.1)
  dim(topset1)

Something you learned earlier

annot[] <- lapply(annot, as.character)
#colnames(annot)

# store DMCs in results object
res <- DMCs

  res$label <- ifelse(!is.na(res$Gene_Symbol), res$Gene_Symbol, res$CpG_ID)

res$significance <- ifelse(res$adj.P.Val < 0.05 & res$logFC > 0.05, "Hypermethylated",
                                    ifelse(res$adj.P.Val < 0.05 & res$logFC < -0.05, "Hypomethylated", "Not Significant"))

# Order topTable_res by adjusted p-value
res <- res[order(res$adj.P.Val), ]

# Create the volcano plot
volcano_plot <- ggplot(res, aes(x = logFC, y = -log10(adj.P.Val), color = significance)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +  # Scatter plot with transparency to see point density
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Not Significant" = "gray", "Hypermethylated" = "red", "Hypomethylated" = "blue")) +  # Set custom colors
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log10(0.05), linetype = "dashed", color = "blue") +  # Line indicating p-value threshold
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(-0.05, 0.05), linetype = "dashed", color = "blue") +  # Lines indicating logFC thresholds
  labs(title = "Volcano Plot of Differential Methylation Results",
       x = "Log2 Fold Change (logFC)",
       y = "-Log10 P-Value",
       color = "Gene Significance") +
  theme_minimal() +  # Clean plot theme
  theme(legend.position = "top")

# Add labels to the most significant genes using gene symbols (or Ensembl IDs if symbols are not available)
volcano_plot <- volcano_plot +
  geom_text_repel(data = subset(res, adj.P.Val < 0.01 & abs(logFC) > 0.1),
                  aes(label = label),  # Use the label column which contains either gene symbols or Ensembl IDs
                  size = 3, max.overlaps = 10)

# Print the volcano plot
print(volcano_plot)

2.13 PATHWAY ENRICHMENT ANALYSIS

After we have performed differential methylation analysis, we get long list of significant CpG sites to interpret. One important question is, “which gene pathways are over-represented for differentially methylated CpGs?” Sometimes, it can be easy to link the top DMCs to genes that make biological sense in terms of the cell types or samples being studied, but there may be many thousands of CpGs significantly differentially methylated. In order to gain an understanding of the biological processes that the differentially methylated CpGs may be involved in, we can perform gene ontology or KEGG pathway analysis using the gometh function in the missMethyl package.

2.13.1 Gene Ontology

The gometh takes into account the varying numbers of CpGs associated with each gene on the Illumina methylation arrays. The top 20 gene ontology categories can be displayed using the topGO function. For KEGG pathway analysis, the topKEGG function can be called to display the top 20 enriched pathways.

# Get the significant CpG sites at less than 5% FDR, or use nominal p-values
sigCpGs <- DMCs$CpG_ID[DMCs$adj.P.Val<0.05]

# First 10 significant CpGs
sigCpGs[1:10]
##  [1] "cg18198301" "cg20434422" "cg27456951" "cg02193283" "cg05075579"
##  [6] "cg13017929" NA           "cg24707200" "cg13570892" "cg08271907"
# Total number of significant CpGs at 5% FDR
length(sigCpGs)
## [1] 23699
# Get all the CpG sites used in the analysis to form the background
all <- DMCs$CpG_ID

# Total number of CpG sites tested
length(all)
## [1] 428254
# The gst object is a data.frame with each row corresponding to the GO category being tested

Visualization of GO enrichment plot

# Extract Hyper genes (based on significance column)
Hyper <- res[res$significance == "Hypermethylated", ]

# Extract down-regulated genes (based on significance column)
Hypo <- res[res$significance == "Hypomethylated", ]


# Put the hyper- and hypo gene groups in a named list
GeneClust <- list("Hypermethylated" = Hyper$Entrez_ID, "Hypomethylated" = Hypo$Entrez_ID)

# Run GO enrichment analysis to compare the two groups, focusing on biological processes (BP)
geores <- compareCluster(
  geneClusters = GeneClust,          # List of gene clusters (up- and down-regulated)
  fun = "enrichGO",                  # Enrichment function (GO enrichment)
  OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db,              # Human gene annotation database
  keyType = "ENTREZID",               # Specify that Ensembl IDs are used
  ont = "BP",                        # Ontology: Biological Process
  pAdjustMethod = "BH",              # Adjust p-values using Benjamini-Hochberg method
  pvalueCutoff = 0.05,               # Set p-value cutoff
  qvalueCutoff = 0.05                # Set q-value cutoff
)

# Visualize the enrichment results in a dot plot
dotplot(geores, showCategory = 10, title = "GO Enrichment: Hyper vs Hypo- methylated Genes") +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8))

2.13.2 KEGG enrichment

# Extract Hyper genes (based on significance column)
Hyper <- res[res$significance == "Hypermethylated", ]

# Extract down-regulated genes (based on significance column)
Hypo <- res[res$significance == "Hypomethylated", ]


# Put the hyper- and hypo gene groups in a named list
GeneClust <- list("Hypermethylated" = Hyper$Entrez_ID, "Hypomethylated" = Hypo$Entrez_ID)

# Run KEGG enrichment analysis to compare the two groups using ENTREZ IDs
kegg_res <- compareCluster(
  geneClusters = GeneClust,          # List of gene clusters (up- and down-regulated)
  fun = "enrichKEGG",                # KEGG pathway enrichment function
  organism = "hsa",                  # Human organism ('hsa' for Homo sapiens)
  pAdjustMethod = "BH",              # Adjust p-values using Benjamini-Hochberg method
  pvalueCutoff = 0.05,               # Set p-value cutoff
  qvalueCutoff = 0.1                # Set q-value cutoff
)

# Check if there are any results
if (is.null(kegg_res) || nrow(as.data.frame(kegg_res)) == 0) {
  print("No significant KEGG pathways were found.")
} else {
  # Visualize the KEGG enrichment results in a dot plot
  dotplot(kegg_res, showCategory = 10, title = "KEGG Pathway Enrichment: Up vs Down-regulated Genes") +
    theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8))  
}
